{
  "answer": "**In *San Hyan Mahajnana*, the strongest single passage defining *jñāna* (knowledge/wisdom) equates it directly with the holy *ātmā* (Self), the realization of which yields liberation.**[^1]\n\nThis working definition frames *jñāna* as synonymous with the *ātmā*—the pure, eternal essence beyond states of being—rather than mere cognition or information. It recurs thematically as the subtle, qualityless awareness of inner realities (e.g., *prakṛti* as night, *puruṣa* as sun), realized in the heart-lotus to transcend *saṃsāra*.[^2]\n\n**By contrast, *San Hyan Tattvajnana* presents a different definition: *jñāna* as *cetana* (consciousness)—luminous awareness, retention of teachings, and non-forgetfulness—opposed to *acetana* (unconsciousness: delusion, forgetfulness).**[^3]\n\nHere, *jñāna* is an active mental faculty enabling discernment amid *tattva*s (principles), tied to *Śivatattva* overcoming *Māyātattva*, rather than the *ātmā* itself. While both texts link *jñāna* to liberation via subtle insight, *Mahajnana* identifies it as the *ātmā*'s essence, whereas *Tattvajnana* treats it as consciousness distinguishing truth from illusion.\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-c60edd).\n\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-08aa3a).\n\n[^3]: *San Hyan Tattvajnana*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-san-hyan-tattvajnana-1f29bd/01/translation/#p-daaeef).",
